docs.abstract: With government often more the problem than the solution, communities are taking matters into their own hands. But gains against crime can carry a cost.
docs.snippet: With government often more the problem than the solution, communities are taking matters into their own hands. But gains against crime can carry a cost.
docs.lead_paragraph: TANCÍTARO, Mexico — The road to this agricultural town winds through the slums and cartel-controlled territory of Michoacán, ground zero for Mexico’s drug war, before arriving at a sight so strange it can seem like a mirage.

headline.main: Losing Faith in the State, Some Mexican Towns Quietly Break Away
headline.print_headline: Seceding for Safety, in Pockets Across Mexico

docs.abstract: The United Nations Security Council discussed the recent protests in Iran over economic conditions there.
docs.snippet: The United Nations Security Council discussed the recent protests in Iran over economic conditions there.
docs.lead_paragraph: UNITED NATIONS — Efforts by the Trump administration to marshal a muscular international response to Iran’s crackdown on anti-government protesters appeared to backfire on Friday, as members of the United Nations Security Council instead used a special session called by the United States to lecture the American ambassador on the proper purpose of the body and to reaffirm support for the Iran nuclear agreement.

headline.main: The U.S. Wanted to Discuss Iran. Russia Brought Up Black Lives Matter.
headline.print_headline: Russia and U.S. Joust at U.N. Over Iran Protests

docs.abstract: The Birmingham minister understood white ambivalence about racism.
docs.snippet: The Birmingham minister understood white ambivalence about racism.
docs.lead_paragraph: During my research for a civil-rights history of Birmingham, Ala., a coveted source was proving elusive: the Rev. Wyatt Tee Walker, who had been the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.’s chief of staff during the 1963 demonstrations at my story’s climax — and who died on Tuesday at age 88.

headline.main: Wyatt Tee Walker, Civil Rights Oracle

docs.abstract: We are real people, not a bunch of demographic characteristics.
docs.snippet: We are real people, not a bunch of demographic characteristics.
docs.lead_paragraph: Sept. 16, 2017, had the potential to be an awful day on the National Mall in Washington. It started with a rally, organized by a group of Trump supporters, called the Mother of All Rallies Patriot Unification Gathering. Counterprotesters from a group called Black Lives Matter of Greater New York began shouting at the crowd. The event’s organizers shouted back, and the two sides began moving toward each other. As the situation became more combustible, onlookers recorded the scene on their phones.

docs.abstract: How Dana Loesch, a onetime Democrat, became a Second Amendment spokeswoman too incendiary for some right-wingers to handle.
docs.snippet: How Dana Loesch, a onetime Democrat, became a Second Amendment spokeswoman too incendiary for some right-wingers to handle.
docs.lead_paragraph: DALLAS — Dana Loesch has a biblical inscription tattooed on her forearm, a reference to a passage in the Book of Ephesians that calls for Christians to wear holy armor to protect themselves from a dark world. It is an apt precept for Ms. Loesch, a 39-year-old conservative radio talk-show host and political commentator who views the world through a lens of fear and violence.

headline.main: The National Rifle Association’s Telegenic Warrior

docs.abstract: CW’s latest serial has a race-forward sensibility and a reluctant superhero who grapples with heroism’s limits.
docs.snippet: CW’s latest serial has a race-forward sensibility and a reluctant superhero who grapples with heroism’s limits.
docs.lead_paragraph: What stands out about “Black Lightning” are not the scenes in which the title hero zaps a gajillion volts of justice through a crew of murder-minded gang members. You can already see that sort of thing on CW — home to “The Flash,” “Supergirl,” “DC’s Legends of Tomorrow” and “Arrow” — and the rest of superhero-supersaturated TV.

headline.main: Review: ‘Black Lightning’ Is Pulp With a Purpose

docs.abstract: “When They Call You a Terrorist,” a memoir by Black Lives Matter co-founder Patrisse Khan-Cullors, and “A More Beautiful and Terrible History,” by the historian Jeanne Theoharis, offer insights about the civil rights movement past and present.
docs.snippet: “When They Call You a Terrorist,” a memoir by Black Lives Matter co-founder Patrisse Khan-Cullors, and “A More Beautiful and Terrible History,” by the historian Jeanne Theoharis, offer insights about the civil rights movement past and present.
docs.lead_paragraph: As an activist and a co-founder of the Black Lives Matter movement, Patrisse Khan-Cullors spends a good amount of time talking to others, not infrequently with a bullhorn in her hand. Her childhood, however, was suffused with silence.

headline.main: Black Lives Matter and the Intrepid Lives That Preceded It
headline.print_headline: Peering Beneath The Veils Of Racism
